A black box in your car?
While U.S. road planners struggle to find the money to repair the crumbling highway network, many are beginning to see a solution in a small black box that can easily fit into your car’s dashboard.
The devices that monitor every kilometre that a motorist drives and transmit that information to the authorities are at the heart of Washington’s controversial effort to renovate America’s outdated main road funding system.
The usually tedious design of motorways suddenly sparked intense debate and the emergence of various associations.
Libertarians met with groups of environmentalists and lobbied for the government to use these little lockers to record mileage and possibly where you’re going, and then use that information to compile a tax assessment.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has mentioned a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress cannot agree on whether to continue, some states are not waiting for anything.
They find out how they can move over the next decade to a system in which the driver pays per kilometer of the road he is driving on.
Thousands of motorists have already taken black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real necessity for our nation.
“This is not a matter of choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California State Administration Association, who plans to start tracking mileage for every California motorist in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
This technology serves this purpose.
The incentive is that the U.S.-funded road trust fund at gas stations is at rock bottom.
Americans aren’t buying as much gas as they used to.
Cars travel a lot more miles per gallon.
The federal tax alone, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in the past 20 years.
Due to the current high price of gasoline, politicians are reluctant to raise the tax by even one cent.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently placed tracking devices in 500 cars to test this payment system per kilometre driven.
“In the long run, this seems to be the most logical alternative,” he said.
Experts call it a user fee based on the number of kilometers driven.
Unsurprisingly, this idea appeals to urban liberals, as taxes can be used to change driver behavior patterns, which can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California planners look to this system when planning strategies to meet the goals set out in ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster (a Pennsylvania representative), chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees this as the most functional long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation’s free market representatives are also keen on the idea that drivers will pay for mileage.
“It’s not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The initiative is also supported by two former U.S. transportation ministers, who urged Congress in 2011 to move toward paying per kilometer.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would include about 10,000 cars.
However, the House of Representatives leadership rejected the proposal, and did so because of the concerns of rural lawmakers representing sections of the population whose daily lives often mean covering many miles for work outside the city.
However, several states and cities are moving forward on their own.
The most zealous is Oregon, which included 5,000 drivers in the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon start paying the state tax for mileage, instead of the gasoline tax.
Nevada has completed its pilot project.
New York is investigating the project.
Illinois does this to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 state ministries of transportation, along with coastal states in the east (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) are studying how they can implement this change.
However, this concept does not only have an advocate.
In Nevada, where about 50 cars of volunteers were recently equipped with the device, drivers were concerned that the government was able to monitor their every move.
“Worrying about Big Brother surveillance and similar issues has been a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategy and operations management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t something that people wanted.
As the trial project continued, the American Civil Liberties Union in Nevada warned on its website, "It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-fledged surveillance devices."
There is no need to build a huge cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to record the daily departures and arrivals of individuals.
Nevada is among the few states that are trying to find available technology that would allow the state to track how many miles the car will drive, but not exactly when and where.
If you can do that, Khan said, the public will be calmer.
The hunt for such technology has led some state agencies to a small California company called True Mileage.
Initially, the company was not involved in the action to help the government in taxing drivers.
She wanted to break through the emerging market of legal liability insurance, where drivers would pay based on how much they drive.
But this device that it tests attracts the attention of road network designers, as it does not use GPS and only provides a limited amount of information that is regularly recorded using a modem.
“People will be more willing to go for it if you don’t track their speed and their location,” says Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been a number of major errors in some of these pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers a choice.
They can choose devices with or without GPS.
Or they do not have to take any equipment and instead decide to pay a flat fee based on the average number of kilometers traveled by all the residents of the state.
In other places, they hope the cautious public will embrace the concept if the device can do more, not less.
In the city of New York, traffic officials are trying to develop a tax facility that would be equipped to pay extra parking-hour fees, provide mileage-based insurance, and collect speed data from other drivers so motorists can avoid traffic jams.
“Motorists will be willing to participate in this because of the value of the benefits offered to them,” the city’s design document states.
However, some transport planners would like to know if all the discussions about paying per kilometer are just a huge proxy problem.
Officials at the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Committee say Congress could easily solve the bankrupt trust fund problem by raising the gasoline tax.
A one-off or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid or other cars that do not consume much fuel, so they will pay a fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when aspirin is plentiful,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Committee on Legislation and Public Affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will be worried about their privacy and a lot of other things.
