George Kerevan: Divided Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another scary story about independence.
This time, there is a warning that the condition for independent Scotland’s membership in the EU would be its accession to Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport checks in Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
The truth is that the Strathclyde newspaper mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but, as expected, this was not reflected in the headlines.
No one mentioned that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws if it suits them.
Given that Scotland is not currently in Schengen, an offer of continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession to Brussels in return for whatever they really want from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
I heard a journalist's duck say that "independence means passport control" at least 40 years ago.
Yet there is an interesting idea in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe at all?
Why exchange the London hoop for the Brussels hoop, especially now?
This is a true European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
The so-called “Project Europe” is officially dead.
Across Europe, the parties are gaining influence in opposition to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded this year - came out of nowhere and already took nearly five million votes in the September federal election, effectively sweeping the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
On home soil there has always been resistance to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a defining moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, along with the straitjacket imposed on national economies by sticking to a common currency, has led many people to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running a high budget deficit - this was only true in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of the euro that blocks its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters - and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only help is to cut revenues and public spending, as Germany encourages.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper cause of Europe’s languid performance.
As a result of the "green" energy policy promoted by Brussels - a code for supporting French and German companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as it does in the United States.
This is a paralyzing disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even all the wage freezes in the world would not prevent the stomping of the European petrochemical industry with cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smoldering revolt, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany at bay and allow Paris to rise to Washington’s level in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a major additional election and pushed the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote - an early warning to British Labour that they cannot conclude that the split of the right will automatically have a positive effect on the left.
How does Le Pen handle her newfound popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc working against the common currency across the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in this election, as is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in its history.
It occurs to me that, in the foreseeable future, the growing anti-European sentiment and attitude against the common currency will merge and destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather be transformed into something more free in the sense of the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and align itself with the United States.
However, Washington’s increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
Where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be an area (in principle) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - this includes the possibility of announcing to Berlin and Brussels when they should leave us alone.
I assume that Scotland would do well in a relaxed European order, provided it kept its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and retain our economic independence.
Strangely enough, the SNP government in Scotland is the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, won by a large majority in 2011 thanks to opposition to cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the following coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence just to adopt austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Matured Early
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
Physical changes don't mean puberty is coming.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are involved.
Experts say that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be an epidemic of obesity.
The trend of early puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be terrified when her daughter begins to grow breasts and pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
“I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it wasn’t usually a sign of rapid development toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, in the last forty years there has been only a small shift in the age at which the first menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years old compared to 12.75 years old in 1970.
“When breasts begin to develop, it will be at least two to three years before the first menstruation occurs,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of “Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
It is discussed what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "premature."
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - which can be carefully monitored by pediatricians.
Faster growth may be a reason for an endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones, which can eventually lead to the cessation of growth and stunting in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormonal treatment depend on the child's age, speed of development, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
As for the use of drugs, Kaplowitz is cautious, but recognizes that "the suppression of puberty can alleviate problems with a girl's behavior and her feelings of being different from her peers."
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried that she might get pregnant or how she’ll manage her hygiene,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were hints and we talked about menstruation, it was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is not yet a coherent body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, environmental chemicals, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study on girls between the ages of 6 and 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations vary.
From a global perspective, early puberty patterns appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at an early age, the trend toward full bloom of early puberty is not as clear-cut as it is for girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of Pediatricians (AAP) conference added additional complexity to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryebsk Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their child’s doctor on how to talk to their child.
“It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you think,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if this happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
