New Nicotine Vaccine May Take Away the Pleasure of Smoking
Scientists have developed a vaccine against nicotine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine protected the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
More tests need to be done before human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell School of Medicine in New York says the first indications are good.
"We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found their nicotine dependence so strong to overcome all current approaches," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-smoking antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a smooth flow of these antibodies.
Antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
During the tests, the vaccinated mice, which were additionally supplied with nicotine, continued their normal activities.
But the mice that weren’t vaccinated “sedated,” the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given often enough to maintain a sufficient level of antibodies, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of new vaccines should be much lower as they convert liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, thus avoiding nicotine addiction.
However, smokers are more likely to use it to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not enjoy the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them get rid of this habit," he said.
