Demand across areas in Southeast Asia - where household debt is rising - is indeed such that ValueMax, where the woman is conducting her transaction, has become the third pawnbroker on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Stopping jewelry is not only a quick way to borrow cash - 1300 SGD in the case of Mrs. Amirthalinga - but it is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
pawnbrokers in Singapore routinely apply an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4% rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage of not requiring a person verification (payment history) or proof of income, and can provide a loan faster than banks.
As families feel pressured by rising living costs and rising household debt and consumer debt, millions across the region are turning to pawnshops.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit backed by relaxed monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to deal with the deteriorating financial situation.
