FAA: Air Passengers Can Now Use Technological Advances on Planes (But Not Call From Their Cell Phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices "from gate to gate" - in addition to calling from their mobile phones - to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music based on the eagerly anticipated new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect the changes to take place immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will need to demonstrate to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated cabin crew training manuals and equipment storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve widespread use of electronic devices very quickly,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors close.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches a height of 3 kilometers and the captain issues a permit.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the plane descends to land, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewards Association, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new rules are safely implemented - and we will work closely with transport companies to do so - it will be a success," Glading said in a statement.
