“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigational devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference with broadcast towers in the air,” Rosenker said.
A trade advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue last month proposed that the government allow wider use of electronic devices.
Pressure has been exerted on the FAA in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Missouri Democrat, argue that there is no legitimate security reason for this ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce, as the use of such devices is ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to interference with navigation and communication equipment, as passengers began to carry FM radios, a technical achievement of the time.
The new airlines are much more reliant on electrical systems than the aircraft of previous generations, but they are also engineered, and approved by the FAA administration, to be resistant to electronic interference.
For several years, airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes.
Plans adapted for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
