Scientists Reveal How Tail Movements Are Linked to Dog Mood
Previous research has shown that joyful dogs wag their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wave their tail mostly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different connections to stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
We've been trying to see the same thing in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that these two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs respond to the asymmetric tail-wagging of other dogs, the researchers monitored animals that watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side, and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We screened dog films - whether in the natural version or in the form of a silhouette - to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail and depict it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw an otherwise bland dog moving its tail to the right (from the dog's point of view wiggling its tail), it remained perfectly still.
But when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again, from the point of view of the dog wiggling its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals felt insecure.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and may not watch out for.
He said: "If you meet dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior and the movement to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you will react based on this experience."
Researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a college animal health teacher at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides were important to dogs.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they observe an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a cheerful dog.
In another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were more likely to get acquainted with a dog robot when it waggled its tail to the left than to the right, when it was more likely to become insecure than when it was in an Italian study.”
The difference, he said, may be that dogs in these different studies didn’t interpret animals in movies or canine robots quite like dogs.
He explained that a study on how dogs respond to real dogs might help.
"Although there is strong evidence in the case of many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified - and dogs are no exception," he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
