I close the book here.
Going into the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It is difficult to remember these optimistic days - they seem to be distant memories, sad reminders of missed opportunities.
In the years since I threw in my first ballot, there have actually been changes.
It was definitely not what I had imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied accomplishments, from the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq and the end of the “don’t ask, don’t tell” policy after the death of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I am convinced that the partisan obstructions have reversed so many efforts to move our nation forward: among other things, immigration reform, the public’s ability to choose health care, and the closure of the Guantanamo base.
But after defending the Obama administration in front of many of my colleagues and friends, I have reached the absolute limit when it comes to the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political despair.
The Republicans' obstructionism cannot explain the agreement to eavesdrop on foreign leaders or the drone strikes that are killing innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain that the National Security Agency is collecting data on the private lives of Americans, nor that it is persecuting those who expose the government’s misconduct.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, without due process, nor for curtailing public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of the report, which says that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, they can’t even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that was to be expected.
Whether I should have suspected at the age of 18 that government power might be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
The elected office clearly has no predictable course, and our public conversations will be shaped by opposition political parties and random events such as the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I mentioned above seem to be largely the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confused and unscrupulous alternative, and seemed unable to consolidate his policy or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, freed from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we once heard about.
Yet the return to 2008 - as Obama's support dropped below 45% this week - is making this book harder and harder.
It makes me remember the many promises that have been lost.
This week I read a chapter in a book about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat with Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At an additional meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that they needed to get back on pace and stay true to their mission.
“I want my magic back,” he said.
We must not forget who we are.
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I completely agree with you.
The ideas expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
