RBS Suspends Two Foreign Currency Traders
According to two people familiar with the situation, the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is suspending two traders in its foreign currency division, another indication that a global investigation by regulators into suspected currency market machinations is becoming more frequent.
Some of the world’s largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are working with competent authorities on investigations into the world’s largest financial market, where they are changing owners $5.3 trillion every day.
The two traders would be the first RBS employees suspended as part of an expanding investigation in response to the LIBOR (London Interbank Interest Rate) scandal.
The bank declined to comment on the suspension, but confirmed it had received a request for information from authorities earlier this month.
“Our ongoing investigation continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other authorities,” the bank said in a statement.
Last month, people close to the event reported that RBS had handed over records of emails and instant messages sent from accounts and to the accounts of a former trader to the UK’s financial behaviour authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and is believed to have been relieved of his current position as European Chairman of Foreign Currency Trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European chairman of cash trading at Citi, took a vacation this week, while Matt Gardiner, former head of currency trading at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders were charged with any misdemeanor.
Mr. Usher's instant messaging group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, people familiar with the event said.
UBS said this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator Finma announced that it was investigating suspicious currency market manipulations in several Swiss banks.
Globally, at least six authorities - the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss antitrust office Weko, the FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are investigating claims that these bankers have conspired to move the currency market.
In addition, people familiar with the situation said that HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse launched an internal investigation or received a request for information from the authorities.
Banks are combing through years-old instant messages and e-mails to find cases of misdemeanors.
Reports of investigations have alarmed traders in an area that has been one of the biggest drivers of profit-making in investment bank closings in recent years, but which has been disrupted by the small volatility of currencies limiting opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to reduce the severity of the situation by arguing that a large and highly liquid foreign currency market is essentially impossible to manipulate, but high-ranking traders say this is not necessarily true.
The high-ranking trader said that despite the significant volume of daily foreign currency trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and banks, increasing the use of their own internal platforms, means that “you can start to influence the market at relatively low prices.”
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it had fired a trader from its stock trading department this week, causing a loss of nearly $6 million at the end of last year.
The bank immediately notified the competent authorities and cooperates with their control authorities.
“We are convinced that this trader acted alone and that this issue has been resolved,” Credit Suisse said in a statement.
