Google, Samsung and Huawei sued over Nortel patents
The group, which owns thousands of patents for the defunct company Nortel, filed a patent infringement lawsuit Thursday against mobile phone makers, including Google, a company it auctioned off as part of Nortel's bankruptcy.
The Rockstar consortium, which bought Nortel’s patents for $4.5 billion, sued Samsung Electronics, HTC, Huawei and four other companies in the U.S. District Court in Texas for patent infringement.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, Blackberry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google has been accused of infringing seven patents.
The patents include technology that helps link search terms on the Internet to relevant advertising, according to the lawsuit, which is at the heart of Google’s search business.
Representatives from Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar were not immediately available.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC are making phones that run on Google’s Android operating system, which competes heavily with Apple and Microsoft’s mobile products.
In 2011, Google made a default price offer of $900 million for Nortel patents.
Google increased its offer several times and eventually offered up to $4.4 billion.
After Nortel was defeated by Rockstar, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a deal partially motivated by Motorola's patent family.
“Despite the failure to obtain the patents at issue in the auction, Google has infringed and continues to infringe the patents,” the lawsuit said.
Rockstar is seeking increased damages from Google because it claims that Google’s patent is being infringed intentionally, as the lawsuit alleges.
