Egypt appoints first freely elected president
Mohamed Morsi has taken the inaugural oath, but his triumphal day will hardly end the political unrest in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Mohamed Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he was inaugurated as the country’s first freely elected president, after Hosni Mubarak, who had been deposed 16 months earlier.
In his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took the oath in front of 18 judges dressed in black gowns in a mansion built overlooking the Nile, which resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“The Egyptian people today laid the foundation for a new life of absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer educated in the US and a member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been targeted by governments for most of 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. in a small motorcade, hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and contrary to the presidential pomp of the Mubarak period, traffic was only briefly halted so that the column could pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs to the south.
Morsi’s personal prestige, mockingly referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood’s non-charismatic “reserve tire,” has skyrocketed since his victory and his Friday speech, which aimed to present him not only as an Islamist candidate, but also all those who want to carry out a revolt against authoritarian Mubarak to the end.
“Egypt is today a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Morsi, dressed in a blue social suit with a red tie, told judges in a wood-covered chamber where he took the oath.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to deliver his inaugural address.
While standing at attention, he received an official welcome from the military band that played the national anthem.
A military commander, Field Marshal Hussein Tantavi, was present.
His arrival was accompanied by chanting "the army and the people are one hand" from the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
The University of Cairo was founded in 1908 as a center for secular education and later in the 1970s became a bastion of Islamic student movements.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, where the revolution that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year was born, and solemnly promised to seize back the presidential powers taken from his office by a military council that took them from the ousted leader.
But agreeing to take an official oath before the court, rather than before parliament, as is customary, has yielded to the will of the military, indicating that the power struggle will continue.
Morsi’s speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
There are likely to be police specialists in the ghettos, they are supposed to relieve tension
In the future, there should be police specialists in the ghettos in the Czech Republic.
They would spend up to half of their errands here.
They would keep order and solve problems.
Thanks to their knowledge of the environment, they should contribute to reducing the tension between people from poor places and residents from the surrounding area.
In its proposal to reduce security risks, the Ministry of the Interior counts on this.
In his view, improving the situation in the country would mainly help "accelerated provision of social housing".
The document was discussed by the government.
According to the analysis, there were about 300 poor houses and neighborhoods in the Czech Republic a few years ago.
About 80,000 people lived there, mostly Roma.
Adults in the ghettos were out of work, families were dependent on benefits, children ended up in "special" schools.
It's been usury.
According to experts, the number of problem locations has increased by 100.
Relations between their people and others are intensifying.
Anti-Romani marches were held in several places.
People from the area also joined the extremists.
According to the Interior Ministry, it is difficult for the police to maintain security and order in areas with ghettos.
A key condition is "consistent application of equal treatment in law enforcement".
But this is not possible without detailed knowledge of the place and people.
A specialist would go on errands in the ghetto, where he would spend up to half his service, the rest would serve in his district.
In a troubled location, he would oversee order.
He would also know the locals, so he could better solve problems or misdemeanors.
"Thanks to the established trust, specialists will be able to prevent a whole range of illegal activities more easily," the Interior Ministry said.
Specialists in ghettos would receive surcharges of 500 to 1000 crowns per month.
The introduction of special police officers to problem areas is to be covered by Norwegian funds.
The budget is about 600,000 euros (currently about 15.5 million crowns).
The Czech Republic pays 15 percent of the amount, the funds 85 percent.
Preparations began this year, now a detailed proposal is being prepared.
The project is to last until 2016.
The authors were inspired by their neighbors.
This mechanism has been successfully applied in Slovakia for several years, where the problem with socially excluded localities is incomparably higher than in the Czech Republic.
"There are so-called Romani settlements," the authors of the report said.
How many specialists there should be in the Czech Republic is not yet clear.
The answer is to give an analysis that will determine the places where a special policeman would be needed.
It will also depend on how much money the police will be able to release each year after the end of the project.
According to the project proposal, the selected police officers will first complete an internship in Slovakia.
Each year, five hundred people are trained in this field.
They will be the most suitable candidates.
There should also be special education for police officers who will work in ghettos.
According to the authors, social housing would help to improve the situation.
It should motivate and lead to integration.
According to the interior design, it would have three categories.
The minimum standard would be met by hostels with strict rules, such as the number of people per room.
The middle standard would be in smaller apartments.
Social housing would have a higher standard, which would be comparable to normal housing.
Tenants would have to follow an integration plan drawn up with them by social workers.
They would have to comply with the accommodation rules, take care of their health, send children to schools, retrain and actively look for work.
If they tried to integrate, they would move to a higher standard of living.
A permeable housing system should operate for at least 30 years, according to the Interior Ministry, until the next generation grows "in a pro-integrationally-motivated environment".
The model of social housing is prepared by local development and labor ministries.
They will propose it by the end of the year.
Karel Drábek: Coal Hill - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Uhlířský vrch is a prominent hill 3 km southeast of Bruntál.
Together with several others, it is a proof of volcanic activity in the Low Jeseníky Mountains in the recent period (from the geological point of view).
The last eruptions were still at the beginning of the Quaternary.
Viewed from a greater distance, the white plastered Baroque pilgrimage church of Our Lady of Help, built in 1755 - 1765, is prominent on the top of the Uhlířský vrch hill.
It replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn that stood next to the church was not preserved.
Shortly after the completion of the church, an alley from four rows of lime trees, about 1 km long, was planted.
The cross road on Uhlířský vrch is the third version, the original one stood here after 1916, the second one, from 2001, lasted only until 2004.
At fifteen stops there are wooden sculptures made by local art carver František Nedomlel.
He used different types of trees from the Low Autumn area.
Similarly, pedestals from rocks from the local area form an interesting geological exposition.
The name of the sponsor is also mentioned at each stop.
The coal hill is the remains of a young volcano.
Although radiometric measurements of age vary somewhat, the last eruption was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than the Great Roudny (3.3 million years old) and older than the Venusian volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born from an explosion.
In doing so, it ejected significant amounts of volcanic ash along with rock fragments from the bedrock, which acquired a reddish-brown color by burning.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters powerful.
The second eruption ejected red, brown-red, and at times black tuffs.
Their layer is powerful up to 50 meters, and part of it is accessible in the wall of the quarry.
In the tuffs there are noticeable volcanic pumas up to 1 meter. Even the second eruption was ended by lava flow.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed from the volcano, which today forms up to 50 m thick layer of slag basalt.
Volcanoes that alternate between volcanic ash and lava flows are the most common type of volcanoes.
Because they are actually composed of stratovolcanoes, they are called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone was gradually eroded.
However, it was threatened only by mining rocks in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in the years 1953 - 1962.
Tuffs were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public, thus preserving this unique place.
However, the problem is in the porosity and small cohesion of the rocks, which quickly weather, disintegrate and slide down the slope down.
The quarries are disappearing quite quickly.
To make the situation even more complicated, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal place for some rare species of plants and animals.
Correction is therefore problematic, but in time it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
This is nothing new, similar profiles are maintained on a number of important sites.
You can get to Uhlířský vrch by following the green tourist trail from Bruntál or Slezský Kočov.
Drivers can use the free car park at the beginning of the linden alley, where a short educational trail begins.
She moved from the villa to a block of flats.
Ivana grew up and spent most of her life in an apartment villa with a garden and a swimming pool in one of Prague’s most beautiful residential areas in Ořechovka.
However, the original owners of the house got it back in restitution and the tenants had to move out with a small severance payment.
Ivana quickly looked for a replacement home for herself and her then-older mother.
She received a tip for apartment 3 + kk in an older block of flats on the opposite side of Prague.
"At first it was a shock, but the view from the fourth floor to the extensive forest park and dam, on the other hand, impressed me," Ivana recalls the first impression.
At first, I thought it would be a makeshift for about three years.
"Today we live here for more than thirteen years and not only because of the gradual reconstruction I would not change," adds the owner.
At that time, the mother and daughter moved from a one hundred and twenty-meter apartment to a smaller one with an area of 62 m2 and gave away almost all the equipment.
The event was not easy, things were stored with friends and gradual arrangement took almost a year.
The new apartment was in quite good condition, but the necessary adjustments had to be made, for example, painting the doors or replacing the windows.
The previous owner knocked out the core, but the owner was most bothered by the impracticable and unnecessarily large hallway, and vice versa small bathroom.
By combining two rooms, a multifunctional living space was created.
The architects used plasterboard to delineate the zones and divide the room, which allowed the new placement of lights.
The first step she took after a few years was to remove the partition in the living room.
This changed the layout of the apartment to 2 + kk, but the room gained airiness and opened a panoramic view of the surrounding greenery.
The next step in the partial improvement of the standard was the replacement of the PVC floor with a laminate one.
Ivana didn’t know what to do with the bathroom.
I've been taking home magazines for years, looking for inspiration.
In one of them, I recently discovered an interesting implementation.
On my recommendation, I approached the young architect Kamila Douděrová.
“It was the most important step in the future,” Ivana said.
Thanks to the reconstruction of the bathroom, the hall was also modified.
The architect combined the space of the toilet and the bathroom and replaced the two doors with opening wings with one sliding one, thus saving space.
The bathroom is timeless and also wheelchair accessible.
Quality tiles imitate sandstone, in the shower there is also a comfortable seat, at the toilet bidet shower.
The successful cooperation with Kamila Douděrová continued.
As part of the program How to Build a Dream, a quick but fundamental transformation of the living room took place, in which the architect Martin Čeněk also participated.
In the space created by combining two smaller rooms, we had to get three functions, dining, living and sleeping, without using the classical principles of optical division, for example, partitions or Japanese walls.
"This would ultimately violate the openness and unity of the space," explains the architect.
It was possible to separate the sleeping and living areas.
It was enough to turn the backs of two sofas and put a custom-made duvet cabinet between them.
The dining area is defined by the shades of the floor and painting.
For the floor in the kitchen and dining area, the architect used a quality marmoleum, the sliding door revived with wallpaper with a pattern.
The kitchen corner, if necessary, is covered with sliding panels with wallpaper.
The new floor made of anti-allergic marmoleum has a number of advantages over the previous laminate: a softer non-slip surface without joints and better sound insulation.
The system of recesses and suspended ceilings from plasterboard highlighted with color is an example of how to work with space in a panel building.
I left the colors to the architects, I wanted it to be joyful.
"I like orange, I had the same shade in my previous apartment," says Ivana.
The glass paneling with the motif of blooming magnolia is practical and creates a distinctive aesthetic element.
To warm energetic tone, the architects chose white, which underlined the modern functional style.
In a small apartment, we managed to store books, among other things, in the space under the window sills.
Everything is within reach, the lamps are comfortably controlled at a distance.
In the redesigned interior, the contrast of the new with the older one works perfectly, for example with a decades-old crystal chandelier as well as with quality art objects that Ivana has been collecting all her life.
Then came the kitchen.
The lockers had previously been placed on both sides, and the owner felt a bit like a tunnel.
The architect took their numbers and rescheduled the deployment.
Furniture in a simple design is made to order, the white surface is softened by a slightly pearly surface.
Thanks to the ingenious solution, the washing machine, dryer and dishwasher fit into a small space.
The appearance of a small kitchen revived the all-glass cladding of the walls above the worktop.
Unique graph glass with digitally printed motif is attractive, in addition, it is well maintained.
Ivana chose flowers of magnolias that remind her of her favorite neighborhood where she lived for years.
Now she seems to be happy here too.
In the original bathroom was a small bath and sink, to the new owner chose a neutral shade of the cladding.
The large shower has a Ronal glass door.
The task was to create a clear simple space from the given environment, in which the functions and devices will be in harmony.
We unified the interior in material and color and tried on its elegant, cozy, not too crowded look.
"Another condition for the assignment was a barrier-free solution with a minimum of obstacles and the possibility of easy movement around the furniture and the accessibility of everyday objects," adds Kamila Doudírová.
