"But now they have only a few weeks left to move to the new law without complications for their companies," commented Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal partner Jan Spáčil.
Of the 61 percent of companies intensively engaged in the new codes, 26 percent said that their companies have already taken all the necessary measures to be prepared in time.
Furthermore, 35 percent of these companies are preparing to take the necessary measures in the near future.
Against this, every fifth company has not yet dealt with recodifications, yet it has a specific idea how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent do not have an opinion and cannot assess the issue.
Only 8 percent of companies admit that they have not yet addressed the issue of recodification.
The most important legal issue related to the new Civil Code for the largest number of companies surveyed is the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent), followed by the resolution of business conditions (16 percent) and further changes in the land register and liability for damage (ten percent).
For contracts, one of the most important novelties of the whole recodification will take place, namely the unification of the contract regulation only under the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Code will cease, as a result of which the contract law should become clearer for both citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many novelties with an emphasis on greater freedom of organization of relations," said attorney Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal Lukáš Poddaný.
In the context of the Business Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the liability of statutory bodies to be the most important issue.
