It travels through mud, river and jungle and provides free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in the villages of Cameroon.
Bwelle and his team treat hundreds of patients every weekend
There are not many doctors in the West African countries; only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or via your mobile phone.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 nominees for the 2013 CNN Heroes of the Year award.
In the 2013 CNN Heroes of the Year competition, you can vote for him or any of the other ten main candidates.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father fall unconscious again and again, driving to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Cameroon's capital Yaounde in 1981.
At first, he was treated only with a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to the brain, and there he developed a hematoma that caused him problems all his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received the kind of treatment that was simply available.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle says.
You can leave the house at five in the morning, rush to the hospital to be there first, but you are not the first.
There's a lot of patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 residents.
And even if Cameroonians could visit doctors, many could not afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare spending in this country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Bwelle says.
Because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his countrymen suffer, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on the weekend, where they provide medical care for free.
Since 2008, nearly 32,000 people have helped with their group of volunteers.
Nearly every Friday, he and up to 30 people cram into vans, attach to rooftops of medical supplies, and travel rough terrain to villages in need of help.
They are not always accompanied by happiness.
More than once, vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as true heroes: feasting, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the community can offer.
In these villages, free medical care is indeed a reason to celebrate, and Bwelle - with his broad smile and unbridled energy - is very eager to engage in local mirth.
The next day, the team begins treating hundreds of patients.
“We have 500 patients on each trip,” Bwelle says.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide a variety of medical assistance.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches or gifted glasses or a free birth certificate - a document that the school demands, but which many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually done in the school building, at the town hall, or at home; after the operation, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery site to make room for the next patient.
Using light from the generator, the operating room, and hygiene equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work into the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team not to lose motivation.
“To stay awake and keep working, they play drums all night,” Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of their work.
The group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, performed 700 free surgeries last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to the local population.
One man said that after the hernia surgery he would be able to work again.
“This will change our family’s future,” the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private medical clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says that this second job funds about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
“I’m not sure when he’s actually asleep,” says Katie O’Malley, who is a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer for Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization to be able to do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who have come from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, this is a great practice they would not get at home.
“We thoroughly washed Dr. Bwell’s hands and removed blood stains or held his tools,” O’Malley said.
You'll never experience that as a second-year medical student in America.
Students volunteers usually pay for the trip to Cameroon themselves and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaounde, food, transportation, and study are provided by Bwelle.
“He’s a hero,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, constant weight isn't a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy doing this job,” Bwelle says.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
To make people laugh, to ease their pain - that's why I do it.
